; v0.3 Track A: capability-scope convergence case for the evaluation corpus.
;
; `log.i64` requires the *scoped* `log` capability, which — unlike the ambient
; `rng` — is granted lexically by a `(with (log) ...)` form, never by an effect
; row. Written without a scope, `annotate` uses `log.i64` outside any grant, so
; the effect gate rejects it with CAPABILITY_NOT_IN_SCOPE. The only admissible
; repair is `wrap_in_capability_scope`: the loop wraps the op in `(with (log) …)`
; and re-checks. This is the distinct-from-widen convergence the loop could not
; produce before v0.3 (a scoped capability is not row-grantable, so widening is
; inapplicable).
;
; `log.i64` is modeled as an identity-with-side-effect (yields its argument), so
; the oracle stays deterministic and checkable while the capability is genuinely
; exercised. Real emission with native/wasm parity is Track B.
(module logscope
  (fn annotate (params (a i64)) (ret i64)
    (body (call log.i64 (ref a)))))
